  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Originated from efforts to hide criminal proceeds and evade taxation\n\n2. Initial Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Legislation:\n- United States Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive AML legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global problem\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Anti-Drug Abuse Act (1988)\n- US Annunzio-Wylie Anti-Money Laundering Act (1992)\n- US Patriot Act (2001) - Expanded AML regulations post-9/11\n\n5. Global Expansion:\n- United Nations conventions\n- FATF recommendations\n- European Union directives\n- Increased international cooperation in detecting and preventing money laundering\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve with technological and financial innovations.",
